<div id="review_3324679485" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3324679485" />
    <a title="Kezia Tabago" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/104818863-kezia-tabago"><img alt="Kezia Tabago" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3324679485?book_show_action=true">May 07, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kezia Tabago" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kezia Tabago" href="/user/show/104818863-kezia-tabago">Kezia Tabago</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3324679485" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15640078077067256787">All I can say is: I cannot put this book down!<br/><br/>This book proves that we can be c-suite executives and still be blind about fundamentals. This book comes to the rescue when it comes to dissonance in teams, miscommunication, lapses in decision making and business failures. There is much to know about business decisions and rational thinking given so many potholes, however, this material keeps us in check. Points raised in this book serve as backbone to questions we may have in the internet of thing</span>
  <span id="freeText15640078077067256787" style="display:none">All I can say is: I cannot put this book down!<br /><br />This book proves that we can be c-suite executives and still be blind about fundamentals. This book comes to the rescue when it comes to dissonance in teams, miscommunication, lapses in decision making and business failures. There is much to know about business decisions and rational thinking given so many potholes, however, this material keeps us in check. Points raised in this book serve as backbone to questions we may have in the internet of things. A key take-away here that could’ve served a big part in my decisions was making them and choosing the best option after a thorough evaluation using probabilistic thinking and multi-attribute utility. I am guilty of various biases because most aspects are related to emotions, thus making me blind-sided to many areas. It surprised me that Dr. Tsipursky has a special portion in his journal about mistakes and learning and his story about the computation about purchasing a home. It just goes to show that people need to take a step back and create a system for decisions, personal or business. If there’s one thing that helps improve decision making processes, it is having to make decisions based on choices associated to numerical values. It is difficult enough to put a handle on non-monetary considerations, and the pointers in this book addressed that issue through a solid example. Another key take-away from this book is attentional bias. When I first started working, I tend to make rash decisions (again, I was guilty of another bias – overconfidence bias) and I spent little evaluation on different possibilities. It made me sort of reminiscent and it made me remember t always take into consideration all possible options and outcomes.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15640078077067256787" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


