  <span id="freeText7823284471197882107" style="display:none">The seven steps for avoiding disastrous decisions is one of the best lessons for me to take my decision in a right way. And also ranking between the choices and differentiate them by giving them numbers will help me to find the best alternative. I think it’s a great book to develop your decision making skill.<br /><br />I was trying to land a better career by changing cities. On that situation I read this book and I was able to rank my choices and find the best alternative. I made the ranking and found that my current city stands out and was the best choice for me.<br /><br />The ranking system really surprised me and I’ve learned that we can rank between our choices and find out the best choice by giving them different ranks. I’ll definitely take this lesson and will apply it to my future operation.<br /><br />I think I am vulnerable to planning fallacy bias. Sometimes I feel that everything is going to go according to plan, I don’t pay nearly enough attention to potential problems and fail to account for them in my plans. From now I’ll anticipate the kind of problems that might come up in advance and decide the strategies I am going to use to address them. And I’ll reserve quite a lot of resources, of time, money, social capital, whatever relevant to the project to address the planning fallacy, to address the planning fallacy, to address unanticipated threats, as well as to address unanticipated opportunities, that I don’t want to miss out.</span>
