        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3252738363" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7719245161795004940">Basically, I love to fact check what anyone conveys to be the &quot;Truth&quot;. The spread of fake news is so alarming these days. Hence, when I saw this book entitled, Truth-Seeker&apos;s Handbook, it was a mystery at first. But will definitely be a guide for anyone who desires to know the truth at all times. This book proved me wrong in my choices of being too positive to a point that I forgot about optimism bias. Every aspiring leader and researcher needs to read this book.<br/><br/>My favorite part of this book is </span>
  <span id="freeText7719245161795004940" style="display:none">Basically, I love to fact check what anyone conveys to be the "Truth". The spread of fake news is so alarming these days. Hence, when I saw this book entitled, Truth-Seeker's Handbook, it was a mystery at first. But will definitely be a guide for anyone who desires to know the truth at all times. This book proved me wrong in my choices of being too positive to a point that I forgot about optimism bias. Every aspiring leader and researcher needs to read this book.<br /><br />My favorite part of this book is on Chapter 8 -Avoiding Professional Disasters With Behavioral Science. If only I read this book earlier, I wouldn't have made poor choices in hiring some members of my team who I previously worked with. I was so confident in their boldness to handle a task and expected so much from them. But somehow, they were just "talkers" and ended up as liabilities.<br /><br />It is true that researchers have found that our brains make systematic and predictable errors - what behavioral scientists call cognitive biases -that lead us to make poor decisions, such as overconfidence effect, optimism bias, and planning fallacy. Optimism Bias - Overconfidence feeds into another thinking error, optimism bias, which refers to us being excessively optimistic about the future. Studies show we tend to believe our risk of suffering negative events is less than it actually is and we overestimate the likelihood of positive events. We fall into optimism bias frequently in the workplace and overemphasizing the benefits of projects and understating the costs.<br /><br />I learned about the optimism bias and I am a victim of the overconfidence effect. I will have to implement the strategies stated in this book. It will help me make better decisions in the future.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7719245161795004940" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
