<span id="freeTextContainer271853032151519751">Read this on Kindle. I love the concept of this book but the execution was clumsy. The memes were not cleanly executed and looked a bit off. They were less the common definition of memes and more just smart advice on stock photos. <br/><br/>There were a few typos and formatting errors. Also, Chapter 52 and 53, despite having different titles, have nearly identical text. <br/><br/>The positives:<br/><br/>I enjoyed most the chapters that applied EGRIP (Emotions, Goals, Rapport, Information, Positive Reinforcement.) EGRIP is a </span>
  <span id="freeText271853032151519751" style="display:none">Read this on Kindle. I love the concept of this book but the execution was clumsy. The memes were not cleanly executed and looked a bit off. They were less the common definition of memes and more just smart advice on stock photos. <br /><br />There were a few typos and formatting errors. Also, Chapter 52 and 53, despite having different titles, have nearly identical text. <br /><br />The positives:<br /><br />I enjoyed most the chapters that applied EGRIP (Emotions, Goals, Rapport, Information, Positive Reinforcement.) EGRIP is a technique for getting someone of a different opinion to meet you in the common ground of facts. <br /><br />Unfortunately, the EGRIP chapters dealt with Trump stupidities long out of the news. Since Trump produces idiocy rapidly, such chapters felt old. Those topics are better suited for a blog post. <br /><br />Still, this book fills a need. We can all use a reminder that our emotions steer us away from facts. <br /><br />The book seems rushed. With a clean, user-friendly, share-ready presentation, the ideas could have a positive impact on our information-heavy culture. <br /><br />Larry Nocella<br />Author of the novel, Razor Wire Karma, available on Amazon</span>
